WEBVTT

1
00:00:03.638 --> 00:00:06.073
-(METAL DOOR CREAKING)
-(CLOCK TICKING)

2
00:00:11.713 --> 00:00:13.480
(CREAKING CONTINUES)

3
00:00:15.717 --> 00:00:17.384
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

4
00:00:18.987 --> 00:00:21.523
(METAL DOOR OPENING)

5
00:00:24.258 --> 00:00:25.727
(METAL DOOR SLAMS SHUT)

6
00:00:28.328 --> 00:00:31.331
-(TICKING CONTINUES)
-(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

7
00:00:32.800 --> 00:00:34.301
(METAL DOOR OPENS)

8
00:00:34.401 --> 00:00:35.570
PRISON GUARD: <i>Open 15.</i>

9
00:00:37.404 --> 00:00:39.373
-(DOOR LOCK CLICKING)
-(DOOR BUZZING)

10
00:00:40.307 --> 00:00:42.911
(METAL DOOR RUMBLING. OPENING)

11
00:00:43.011 --> 00:00:44.879
-(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)
-(KEYS JANGLING)

12
00:00:44.979 --> 00:00:46.648
(SHEETS RUSTLING)

13
00:00:46.748 --> 00:00:47.949
PRISON GUARD: Hey. get up!

14
00:00:48.482 --> 00:00:50.417
You got a visitor. Look alive.

15
00:00:50.518 --> 00:00:51.686
(DOOR BUZZING)

16
00:00:51.786 --> 00:00:54.321
(METAL DOOR RUMBLING. OPENING)

17
00:00:58.091 --> 00:00:59.561
Becket.

18
00:01:00.427 --> 00:01:03.430
I'm Father James Morris.
one of the chaplains here.

19
00:01:03.932 --> 00:01:05.465
How are you feeling today?

20
00:01:09.369 --> 00:01:10.605
(BECKET GRUNTS SOFTLY)

21
00:01:17.177 --> 00:01:18.412
Cheesecake?

22
00:01:19.079 --> 00:01:20.080
No. thank you.

23
00:01:20.180 --> 00:01:22.382
BECKET: You know.
I ordered vanilla

24
00:01:22.482 --> 00:01:24.052
and they brought me chocolate.

25
00:01:25.053 --> 00:01:26.286
Kill me now.

26
00:01:27.755 --> 00:01:30.725
So. Father. appreciate you
coming down here.

27
00:01:30.825 --> 00:01:33.528
but I'm fine.

28
00:01:33.628 --> 00:01:35.930
Well. forgive me.
but most people

29
00:01:36.030 --> 00:01:38.198
in your position
feel a bit differently.

30
00:01:38.298 --> 00:01:40.100
Well. I'd argue
most people in my position.

31
00:01:40.200 --> 00:01:41.368
most people. in general.

32
00:01:41.468 --> 00:01:44.237
lack my sense of clarity.
presence of mind.

33
00:01:45.305 --> 00:01:46.473
FATHER MORRIS:
I don't mean to overstep.

34
00:01:46.574 --> 00:01:48.743
but. um. this may be
the last opportunity

35
00:01:48.843 --> 00:01:51.579
you have to speak to anyone.

36
00:01:53.648 --> 00:01:55.550
Is there nothing
you'd like to share?

37
00:01:56.951 --> 00:01:59.119
(TICKING CONTINUES)

38
00:02:01.421 --> 00:02:04.124
BECKET: You know
why I'm here. right?

39
00:02:05.593 --> 00:02:08.128
-I know a little.
-BECKET: Well. it's not true.

40
00:02:10.397 --> 00:02:13.333
The real story.
it's much more...

41
00:02:15.202 --> 00:02:17.038
impressive.

42
00:02:17.137 --> 00:02:19.206
Do you want
to tell me about it?

43
00:02:21.141 --> 00:02:22.342
Well...

44
00:02:23.745 --> 00:02:24.812
I should warn you...

45
00:02:26.814 --> 00:02:27.915
it's a tragedy.

46
00:02:29.449 --> 00:02:31.418
And it doesn't even
start with me.

47
00:02:32.020 --> 00:02:33.420
Funny enough.

48
00:02:33.955 --> 00:02:35.422
it starts with someone else.

49
00:02:36.924 --> 00:02:38.092
<i>And by that I mean. my mother.</i>

50
00:02:38.191 --> 00:02:39.894
...has completely
forgotten how to play.

51
00:02:39.994 --> 00:02:43.163
<i>...Mary Estella Redfellow.</i>

52
00:02:43.263 --> 00:02:45.767
<i>Longtime resident</i>
<i>of Huntington. Long Island.</i>

53
00:02:47.367 --> 00:02:49.570
<i>an heiress</i>
<i>to a family fortune</i>

54
00:02:49.671 --> 00:02:53.107
<i>valued then at 18.</i>
<i>19 billion US dollars.</i>

55
00:02:53.206 --> 00:02:55.109
-Thank you.
-(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

56
00:02:55.208 --> 00:02:56.276
BECKET: <i>Now.</i>
<i>there's a rumor out there</i>

57
00:02:56.376 --> 00:02:58.445
<i>that money</i>
<i>doesn't buy happiness.</i>

58
00:02:58.546 --> 00:03:00.515
Dead wrong.
Money does buy happiness.

59
00:03:00.615 --> 00:03:02.382
We're all adults here.
Let's move on.

60
00:03:02.482 --> 00:03:04.251
(SOFT INSTRUMENTAL
MUSIC PLAYING)

61
00:03:04.351 --> 00:03:06.554
<i>I'm told that the night</i>
<i>she met my father</i>

62
00:03:06.654 --> 00:03:08.422
<i>was a night like any other.</i>

63
00:03:11.491 --> 00:03:14.162
<i>And by that. I mean</i>
<i>she was young. rich.</i>

64
00:03:14.261 --> 00:03:15.897
<i>What could ever go wrong?</i>

65
00:03:17.899 --> 00:03:19.266
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

66
00:03:25.640 --> 00:03:28.109
-MARY: What time is it?
-(COW MOOING)

67
00:03:28.208 --> 00:03:29.143
MARY: Oh. my God!

68
00:03:29.242 --> 00:03:31.079
-CELLIST: What?
-Oh. my God.

69
00:03:31.179 --> 00:03:32.947
-I have to go right now.
-You gotta go now?

70
00:03:33.648 --> 00:03:34.649
MARY: Bye.

71
00:03:40.688 --> 00:03:42.389
(LAUGHING) What are you doing?

72
00:03:42.489 --> 00:03:44.357
-MARY: I have to go.
-Okay.

73
00:03:50.865 --> 00:03:53.233
MAN: <i>I applaud you</i>
<i>for telling us.</i>

74
00:03:53.768 --> 00:03:55.402
<i>That being said.</i>

75
00:03:55.503 --> 00:03:57.505
I think you know
what has to happen.

76
00:03:58.806 --> 00:03:59.741
I'm 18.

77
00:03:59.841 --> 00:04:01.008
Tragically.

78
00:04:02.210 --> 00:04:03.544
No.

79
00:04:03.644 --> 00:04:05.412
This should be my decision.

80
00:04:07.314 --> 00:04:08.583
This should be me.

81
00:04:11.853 --> 00:04:12.920
All right.

82
00:04:13.020 --> 00:04:15.790
You can either get rid of it
or do what you like.

83
00:04:17.357 --> 00:04:18.593
But not here.

84
00:04:19.861 --> 00:04:20.928
Not under this roof.

85
00:04:22.262 --> 00:04:23.998
(SIGHS SOFTLY)

86
00:04:24.098 --> 00:04:26.333
BECKET: <i>In this way. she went</i>
<i>from being Mary Redfellow</i>

87
00:04:26.433 --> 00:04:28.035
<i>of Huntington. New York...</i>

88
00:04:28.136 --> 00:04:29.804
(VEHICLES RUSHING)

89
00:04:29.904 --> 00:04:30.972
<i>...to Mary Redfellow</i>

90
00:04:31.072 --> 00:04:32.707
<i>-of Belleville. New Jersey.</i>
<i>-</i> (TRUCK HORN BLOWS)

91
00:04:32.807 --> 00:04:34.642
-(SCREAMING)
-(DOCTOR MURMURING)

92
00:04:35.375 --> 00:04:36.476
DOCTOR: Breathe.

93
00:04:36.577 --> 00:04:38.079
-(SCREAMING CONTINUES)
-(OBJECTS CLATTERING)

94
00:04:38.179 --> 00:04:39.180
DOCTOR: You're doing well.
Breathe.

95
00:04:39.279 --> 00:04:40.280
MARY: I can't. No. no.

96
00:04:40.380 --> 00:04:41.649
BECKET <i>My father saw me</i>
<i>only once...</i>

97
00:04:41.749 --> 00:04:43.618
-CELLIST: Oh. my God!
-(OBJECTS CLATTERING)

98
00:04:43.718 --> 00:04:45.787
<i>...which was enough to give</i>
<i>him a pulmonary embolism</i>

99
00:04:45.887 --> 00:04:48.388
<i>right there at Jersey City</i>
<i>Memorial Hospital.</i>

100
00:04:48.488 --> 00:04:50.158
...a vehicle that we haven't
seen before...

101
00:04:50.258 --> 00:04:52.560
BECKET: <i>My mother</i>
<i>was left alone</i>

102
00:04:52.660 --> 00:04:55.295
<i>to work at the Newark</i>
<i>Department of Motor Vehicles.</i>

103
00:04:55.395 --> 00:04:56.964
-(TELEPHONE RINGING)
-(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

104
00:04:57.064 --> 00:04:59.700
<i>Pretty soon. she told me</i>
<i>something important.</i>

105
00:05:00.601 --> 00:05:01.836
MARY: In the painting...

106
00:05:01.936 --> 00:05:03.303
BECKET: <i>We may have been</i>
<i>kicked out of the family.</i>

107
00:05:03.403 --> 00:05:05.640
<i>but we weren't kicked</i>
<i>out of the inheritance.</i>

108
00:05:07.275 --> 00:05:10.611
<i>See. my grandfather had</i>
<i>drawn up an irrevocable trust</i>

109
00:05:10.711 --> 00:05:12.246
<i>to avoid paying estate taxes.</i>

110
00:05:12.345 --> 00:05:14.282
<i>It meant that the fortune.</i>

111
00:05:14.381 --> 00:05:16.449
<i>the whole thing.</i>
<i>the real estate.</i>

112
00:05:16.551 --> 00:05:18.385
<i>the boats. the planes.</i>

113
00:05:18.485 --> 00:05:20.588
<i>an island or two.</i>
<i>would be passed down</i>

114
00:05:20.688 --> 00:05:23.524
<i>to the next oldest in line.</i>
<i>no matter what.</i>

115
00:05:24.391 --> 00:05:25.827
<i>And me. being the youngest.</i>

116
00:05:25.927 --> 00:05:28.361
<i>I might inherit</i>
<i>the entire thing someday.</i>

117
00:05:28.461 --> 00:05:30.231
<i>assuming I outlive the others.</i>

118
00:05:30.330 --> 00:05:32.233
(MARY SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY)

119
00:05:32.332 --> 00:05:33.634
BECKET: <i>I just had to wait.</i>

120
00:05:36.436 --> 00:05:37.738
For all of them to die.

121
00:05:38.773 --> 00:05:41.242
-(TICKING CONTINUES)
-(DOOR BUZZING)

122
00:05:41.341 --> 00:05:43.443
(UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING)

123
00:05:46.981 --> 00:05:49.382
BECKET: <i>Now a single mother</i>
<i>doing it all herself.</i>

124
00:05:49.482 --> 00:05:50.551
<i>you might assume</i>

125
00:05:50.651 --> 00:05:52.553
<i>-life was tough. but...</i>
<i>-</i> (DOG BARKING)

126
00:05:53.187 --> 00:05:54.354
<i>...I'll tell you now...</i>

127
00:05:54.454 --> 00:05:55.723
MARY: 'Cause they all sound
the same once you...

128
00:05:55.823 --> 00:05:58.893
<i>...despite our</i>
<i>financial handicap.</i>

129
00:05:58.993 --> 00:06:01.896
<i>she made sure I had all</i>
<i>the culture. class. and style</i>

130
00:06:01.996 --> 00:06:03.396
<i>of a highborn young man.</i>

131
00:06:03.496 --> 00:06:05.498
So when it goes.
it goes through the target.

132
00:06:06.801 --> 00:06:08.569
See how much
of a difference that makes?

133
00:06:08.669 --> 00:06:10.204
-YOUNG BECKET: Mmm-hmm.
-See?

134
00:06:10.304 --> 00:06:11.505
You just open up
your shoulders.

135
00:06:11.606 --> 00:06:13.507
That is so much better.

136
00:06:14.742 --> 00:06:15.475
Okay.

137
00:06:15.576 --> 00:06:17.078
BECKET: <i>That was</i>
<i>the first time...</i>

138
00:06:18.212 --> 00:06:19.914
<i>the first time I saw her.</i>

139
00:06:23.584 --> 00:06:24.886
Julia Steinway.

140
00:06:27.889 --> 00:06:31.058
<i>Right off. I could see</i>
<i>we were the perfect match.</i>

141
00:06:31.158 --> 00:06:33.194
-(CHILDREN EXCLAIMING)
- <i>And clearly. I wasn't wrong.</i>

142
00:06:33.294 --> 00:06:34.494
<i>This was. without a doubt.</i>

143
00:06:34.595 --> 00:06:38.933
<i>a girl of great</i>
<i>social bearing. taste. charm.</i>

144
00:06:39.033 --> 00:06:40.801
JULIA'S MOTHER: What's next?
The big one?

145
00:06:41.602 --> 00:06:42.904
(HORSE WHINNIES)

146
00:06:43.004 --> 00:06:44.372
BECKET: <i>I was</i>
<i>in the right place.</i>

147
00:06:44.471 --> 00:06:46.574
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

148
00:06:50.410 --> 00:06:51.779
What are you doing here?

149
00:06:54.015 --> 00:06:55.082
Your mom invited me.

150
00:06:55.950 --> 00:06:57.417
Where do you live?

151
00:06:57.518 --> 00:06:58.753
Belleville Township.

152
00:06:59.754 --> 00:07:01.122
Do you live on the street?

153
00:07:01.222 --> 00:07:02.489
What?

154
00:07:02.590 --> 00:07:04.625
YOUNG JULIA: I heard people
there live on the street.

155
00:07:05.393 --> 00:07:06.861
I don't live on the street.

156
00:07:07.762 --> 00:07:09.397
And I mean. I won't
be there forever

157
00:07:09.496 --> 00:07:11.464
because I'm supposed
to inherit

158
00:07:11.565 --> 00:07:13.167
a lot of money
or something. so...

159
00:07:13.267 --> 00:07:14.568
YOUNG JULIA:
A lot of money. huh?

160
00:07:15.603 --> 00:07:17.138
Are you trying to impress me?

161
00:07:19.607 --> 00:07:20.875
It's okay if you are.

162
00:07:22.276 --> 00:07:24.045
(SOFT PIANO MUSIC PLAYING)

163
00:07:36.057 --> 00:07:37.525
(AUDIENCE APPLAUDING)

164
00:07:40.428 --> 00:07:42.462
PIANO TEACHER:
Next. we have Lyle Archdale!

165
00:07:46.367 --> 00:07:48.035
(HIGH-TEMPO
PIANO MUSIC PLAYING)

166
00:07:53.207 --> 00:07:54.709
(DISTANT THUNDER RUMBLING)

167
00:07:55.309 --> 00:07:57.378
(ELECTRICAL BUZZING)

168
00:07:57.477 --> 00:07:59.113
-(PIANO MUSIC STOPS)
-(AUDIENCE MURMURING)

169
00:08:00.581 --> 00:08:02.717
PIANO TEACHER: It's all right.
Everyone. it's okay.

170
00:08:04.218 --> 00:08:05.319
Lyle. can you see?

171
00:08:05.419 --> 00:08:06.420
Just keep playing.

172
00:08:06.520 --> 00:08:07.521
(YOUNG BECKET INHALES SHARPLY)

173
00:08:07.621 --> 00:08:08.789
(PIANO MUSIC RESUMES)

174
00:08:16.330 --> 00:08:17.497
(ELECTRICAL BUZZING)

175
00:08:30.778 --> 00:08:31.946
(PIANO MUSIC FADES)

176
00:08:35.282 --> 00:08:36.550
DOCTOR: Hey. Becket.

177
00:08:37.251 --> 00:08:38.486
Can you come with me?

178
00:08:42.456 --> 00:08:44.158
BECKET:
<i>Well. my mother was young...</i>

179
00:08:44.925 --> 00:08:46.560
<i>which is why</i>
<i>she hadn't paid attention</i>

180
00:08:46.660 --> 00:08:48.596
<i>to the symptoms at first.</i>

181
00:08:49.530 --> 00:08:52.133
-Doctors either.
-(CLOCK TICKING)

182
00:08:53.134 --> 00:08:56.237
And the family. um.
I'm sure they knew.

183
00:08:57.738 --> 00:08:59.774
I'm sure they could've helped.

184
00:09:01.208 --> 00:09:02.176
But nothing.

185
00:09:04.645 --> 00:09:06.814
Not one single word.

186
00:09:06.914 --> 00:09:09.083
MARY: <i>Becket.</i>
<i>this is all wrong.</i>

187
00:09:12.620 --> 00:09:13.854
YOUNG BECKET:
What's all wrong?

188
00:09:16.357 --> 00:09:18.159
You should have
more than this.

189
00:09:20.995 --> 00:09:23.264
Something was taken from you.

190
00:09:27.134 --> 00:09:29.703
And I want you
to promise me something.

191
00:09:32.273 --> 00:09:33.641
Will you do that?

192
00:09:34.975 --> 00:09:36.310
Okay.

193
00:09:36.410 --> 00:09:37.645
MARY: Promise me...

194
00:09:38.846 --> 00:09:40.748
that you won't quit...

195
00:09:42.083 --> 00:09:45.219
until you have
the right kind of life.

196
00:09:48.022 --> 00:09:49.524
Until you have
the kind of life

197
00:09:49.623 --> 00:09:52.760
that you deserve to have.

198
00:09:53.828 --> 00:09:55.629
That I raised you to have.

199
00:09:57.865 --> 00:09:59.600
Can you do that for me?

200
00:10:04.939 --> 00:10:07.174
BECKET:
<i>"The right kind of life."</i>

201
00:10:08.642 --> 00:10:10.211
<i>What did she mean by that?</i>

202
00:10:11.745 --> 00:10:13.180
(CHORAL MUSIC PLAYING)

203
00:10:15.049 --> 00:10:16.016
(QUACKING)

204
00:10:17.952 --> 00:10:19.086
BECKET: <i>Her final request</i>

205
00:10:19.186 --> 00:10:21.689
<i>was to be buried</i>
<i>at the Redfellow Mausoleum</i>

206
00:10:21.789 --> 00:10:23.858
<i>on the family plot</i>
<i>in Huntington.</i>

207
00:10:24.692 --> 00:10:25.659
PRIEST: <i>We are</i>
<i>gathered here...</i>

208
00:10:25.759 --> 00:10:26.994
BECKET: <i>When no answer came.</i>

209
00:10:27.094 --> 00:10:29.730
<i>she arrived</i>
<i>at her final resting place</i>

210
00:10:29.830 --> 00:10:32.766
<i>just off the parkway</i>
<i>in East Orange.</i>

211
00:10:34.135 --> 00:10:36.804
PRIEST: And Jesus tells us.
"I am the way.

212
00:10:36.904 --> 00:10:38.739
"the truth. and the life.

213
00:10:38.839 --> 00:10:41.909
"He who has faith..."
Or she indeed...

214
00:10:42.009 --> 00:10:43.911
BECKET: <i>In that moment.</i>
<i>I made up my mind.</i>

215
00:10:44.011 --> 00:10:45.312
<i>Right then and there.</i>

216
00:10:48.716 --> 00:10:51.152
<i>I would go straight</i>
<i>to the source</i>

217
00:10:51.252 --> 00:10:55.022
<i>and demand my rightful place</i>
<i>at my rightful home.</i>

218
00:10:57.124 --> 00:10:58.859
(DOORBELL BUZZES)

219
00:11:15.709 --> 00:11:18.145
-(MUSIC CONTINUES)
-(CAR DOOR CLOSES)

220
00:11:18.245 --> 00:11:19.246
(ENGINE STARTS)

221
00:11:22.149 --> 00:11:23.417
(CAR DEPARTS)

222
00:11:26.987 --> 00:11:29.190
"We hope this finds you well."

223
00:11:32.326 --> 00:11:37.831
After that. I enjoyed
a brief and colorful tour

224
00:11:37.932 --> 00:11:40.134
of the New Jersey
foster care system.

225
00:11:41.869 --> 00:11:45.206
<i>As for Julia.</i>
<i>I saw her less and less...</i>

226
00:11:47.174 --> 00:11:48.175
<i>until finally...</i>

227
00:11:50.344 --> 00:11:51.412
<i>never at all.</i>

228
00:11:53.347 --> 00:11:56.784
<i>And I had to wonder</i>
<i>if we crossed paths again.</i>

229
00:11:57.918 --> 00:11:59.186
<i>who would I be?</i>

230
00:11:59.954 --> 00:12:01.188
<i>A great success?</i>

231
00:12:02.056 --> 00:12:04.258
-(MUSIC STOPS)
- <i>Or no?</i>

232
00:12:05.359 --> 00:12:09.263
-(HORNS HONKING)
-(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

233
00:12:09.363 --> 00:12:12.567
